cussion about Bitcoin’s long-term defensive posture against quantum threats, with BIP-360 described as reshaping a quantum-defense strategy while stopping short of full post-quantum security.\n\nActivity in related ecosystems continues to influence sentiment. A cluster of on-chain and cross-border developments includes Korea's custody-related actions around recovered BTC and the broader pattern of asset redistribution, as well as Bhutan’s state-linked activity — accumulating a substantial BTC stash through national initiatives and later moving to liquidate a portion of holdings in 2026. These moves illustrate how sovereign or quasi-sovereign actors and national-scale infrastructure projects contribute to the discipline and cadence of Bitcoin-related flows.\n\nThe narrative around Ethereum remains relevant as a compare-and-contrast thread. An assessment arguing that Ethereum’s post-Monero-like deflationary narrative (or Ultrasound Money framing) may have fallen short since the shift to Proof-of-Stake signals a structural pivot in investor expectations. The takeaway is a reminder that Ethereum’s dynamic is closely watched for its implications on relative strength versus Bitcoin, even as BTC screens as the more dominant driver in the near term.\n\nIn terms risk and volatility catalysts, several pieces point to potential sharp moves driven by liquidity dynamics around key thresholds and by macro/filed shocks. Articles describe a scenario where a dip could unfold following liquidity sweeps and a subsequent drive higher or lower, depending on how buyers and sellers interact near critical liquidity clusters. The macro context is echoed by reports of oil-price tensions, dollar dynamics, and geopolitical news shaping risk appetite, even as pockets of resilience emerge through buyers stepping in during pullbacks and through new inflows into Bitcoin-wide investment vehicles.\n\nKey themes and developments\n- Bitcoin leadership vs altcoin weakness: BTC remains the focal point, 