tial upside catalysts (cycle theory continuity, possible golden cross), while rising equity correlation, fragile support levels, altcoin weakness, and stressed mining economics inject caution. The overall sentiment is mixed but leans toward cautious optimism about BTC’s resilience in the near term, tempered by macro-linked downside risk and sector-specific pressures. Sources referenced include Cointelegraph’s coverage of the divergence between BTC and gold (including 21Shares’ macro chief) and Scaramucci’s cycle commentary, CoinDesk’s reporting on gold versus BTC liquidity and mining economics, and the articles discussing BTC’s correlation with equities, ETF-style liquidity dynamics, and geopolitical catalysts.'], 'TSLA': ['Tesla and its ecosystem moved into a bold chip-building initiative on March 21–22, 2026, with Elon Musk unveiling Terafab, a joint venture that brings Tesla together with SpaceX and xAI. The core ambition is to internalize and accelerate semiconductor development across Musk’s ventures, framing Terafab as a high-profile effort in AI, robotics, and aerospace-edge computing. Coverage across The Street, Reuters, The Wall Street Journal, TechCrunch, and Investing.com portrayed Terafab as a transformative, certainly ambitious project, while also signaling investor caution about execution risk. In parallel, Musk announced concrete plans to establish two advanced chip factories in Austin, Texas—one to power Tesla vehicles and humanoid robots, and another aimed at AI data centers in space—marking a physical expansion of the chip-production footprint tied to the Terafab initiative. These developments followed the Terafab launch and were reported by Reuters and The Wall Street Journal, among others, underscoring the company’s push to localize and scale chip manufacturing for its broad ecosystem.\n\nKey themes and developments:\n- Internalization and scale of chip production: Terafab is framed as the most ambitious chip-building effort in Musk’s ecosystem, 