 the stock recently emerging from a stretch of underperformance into a potential near-term upturn.\n\nA core thread is the upcoming earnings catalyst and how traders are framing it. Yahoo Finance’s coverage notes that Tesla, alongside other major names, is among the companies whose results are awaited, signaling that the earnings print is a focal point for attention next week. This theme is reinforced by pieces that describe Tesla’s stock as having snapped an eight-week losing streak and being positioned to finish the week higher as earnings approach (Yahoo Finance). One article goes further, suggesting Tesla is on track to end the week with roughly a 15% gain, underscoring a momentum shift tied to the earnings event (Yahoo Finance Video). Yet there is a balance in the narration: market watchers are aware of the earnings as a potential catalyst, but the framing remains non-committal about the direction of the stock beyond the immediate pre- and post-earnings period (Yahoo Finance Video; Yahoo Finance).\n\nTiming details around the earnings appear variably across outlets. One piece mentions that earnings are due next Wednesday, while another points to earnings on Tuesday, April 22. The core takeaway is that the market is braced for a near-term earnings print, with analysts and reporters discussing what to watch and how the results could influence the stock’s trajectory (Yahoo Finance; Yahoo Finance Video). This aligns with the broader narrative of a stock that has been recovering from a multi-week lag into a potentially pivotal earnings moment.\n\nBeyond the headline numbers, a notable thematic thread in the Tesla-specific material is the attention paid to growth avenues that could influence expectations around the company’s trajectory. A Benzinga article about Tesla’s FSD (full self-driving) program frames it as a strategic growth item, highlighting a subscription-based model and ongoing discussions about whether the software is being “gamified” to encourage broader